==English==
===Etymology===
From Latin ''[[uvula#Latin|uvula]]'', from ''[[uva]]'' "grape; uvula" + ''[[-ula]]'' "little".
===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|pl='''[[uvulas]]''' or '''[[uvulae]]'''}}

# {{anatomy}} the piece of [[flesh]] in one's [[mouth]] that [[hang]]s down from the [[palate]]
===Usage note===
Although the '''uvula''' itself is well known, the name for it is not. The Oxford English Dictionary, second edition (1989) marks the word ''uvula'' as "not naturalized, alien" to English.

A common informal name is ''"'''[[dangly thing]]'''"''. Some refer to it as ''"'''[[tonsils]]'''"'', though in standard usage it refers to distinct, nearby organs.
